# Project Proposal — Drone Field Analysis System
**TC1030 — Object-Oriented Programming**
**Author:** Valeria Jiménez | A01714375

## Problem Statement
Modern agriculture faces the challenge of efficiently managing large field zones
with limited resources. This program simulates a drone equipped with a camera 
scanner that analyzes agricultural zones and generates prioritized recommendations
for irrigation and fertilization, helping farmers optimize their fields.
This is a personal project that I started a few months ago. I would like to 
help Mexican agriculture with an intelligent drone built at a lower cost, 
designed and manufactured in Mexico using recycled materials.

## Domain
Agricultural technology / precision farming simulation.

## Why OOP?
The problem naturally maps to objects: a Drone has a CameraScanner, field zones
have measurable properties, and recommendations share behavior but differ in 
implementation. Inheritance and polymorphism allow the system to handle multiple
recommendation types uniformly, while composition models the real-world 
relationship between a drone and its camera.

## Class List
| Class | Role | OOP Concept |
|---|---|---|
| `FieldZone` | Represents a field zone with moisture and nutrient levels | Encapsulation, invariants, exception handling |
| `Recommendation` | Abstract base for all recommendations | Abstract class, virtual destructor, pure virtual methods |
| `IrrigationRec` | Irrigation recommendation | Inheritance, runtime polymorphism, operator overloading |
| `FertilizerRec` | Fertilization recommendation | Inheritance, runtime polymorphism |
| `CameraScanner` | Sensor that scans a field zone | Encapsulation, composition part |
| `Drone` | Owns a camera, scans zones | Composition, RAII, std::vector |
| `FieldManager` | Coordinates drones and recommendations | Smart pointers, aggregation, polymorphic dispatch |
